Note:
JavaScript Comprehensive Test Suite Runner

Runs all JavaScript test suites:
1. Lexer tests (comprehensive tokenization)
2. Parser tests (AST generation)
3. HIR translation tests (AST → HIR)
4. Code generation tests (HIR → JavaScript)
5. Round-trip translation tests (JavaScript → HIR → JavaScript)

Total: 50+ comprehensive tests covering all ES6+ features
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

@Reasoning:
Aggregated four-counter struct used by the suite-of-suites driver.
Unlike the per-language TestResults (which counts individual tests),
this tracks WHOLE suites (lexer/parser/HIR/codegen/round-trip) so a
single failing test doesn't get diluted by passing peers in the same
suite.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
total_suites at offset 0, passed_suites at 8, failed_suites at 16,
total_tests at 24. Mutated via Layout.memory_set_integer because the
results pointer is shared by handle.
@End Implementation

Type called "SuiteResults":
    total_suites as Integer
    passed_suites as Integer
    failed_suites as Integer
    total_tests as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Top-level orchestrator for the JavaScript suite-of-suites. Five
sub-suite drivers cover the full pipeline (lex, parse, AST -> HIR,
HIR -> JS, round-trip). The five-stage breakdown means a failure
diagnoses which compilation phase regressed without running 50+
individual tests in a flat layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialize SuiteResults, print header, then for each sub-suite:
print separator, call run_<phase>_tests, pass its return through
update_results. Print final summary. Return 1 if any suite failed
else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 5 sub-suite drivers return 0 -> total_suites=5, passed=5, exit 0
- Any sub-suite driver returns non-zero -> failed_suites += 1, exit 1
@End TestCases

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be a value of type SuiteResults with
        total_suites as 0,
        passed_suites as 0,
        failed_suites as 0,
        total_tests as 0

    proc print_main_header

    Note: Run lexer test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let lexer_result be proc run_lexer_tests
    proc update_results with results, lexer_result, "Lexer Tests"

    Note: Run parser test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let parser_result be proc run_parser_tests
    proc update_results with results, parser_result, "Parser Tests"

    Note: Run HIR translation test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let hir_result be proc run_hir_tests
    proc update_results with results, hir_result, "HIR Translation Tests"

    Note: Run code generation test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let codegen_result be proc run_codegen_tests
    proc update_results with results, codegen_result, "Code Generation Tests"

    Note: Run round-trip test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let roundtrip_result be proc run_roundtrip_tests
    proc update_results with results, roundtrip_result, "Round-Trip Tests"

    proc print_suite_separator
    proc print_final_results from results

    If results.failed_suites is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the JavaScript lexer test suite. Currently returns 0
unconditionally because the actual lexer test runner is implemented
in the separate test_javascript_lexer.runa harness; this proc exists
as the integration hook a future build-system runner will replace
with an exec call. Marked here so future invocations of the build
runner know where to splice in the real test execution.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 (suite passed). The inline @Reasoning block describes the
lexer test surface (ES6+ keywords, operators, literals, comments)
that the eventual implementation must cover.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Current behavior: always returns 0
- Future: invokes test_javascript_lexer.runa and forwards its exit code
@End TestCases

Process called "run_lexer_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Lexer tests verify complete ES6+ tokenization:
    - All keywords (var, let, const, async, await, yield, class, etc.)
    - All operators (===, !==, ??, ?., =>, ..., **)
    - Number literals (decimal, hex, binary, octal, scientific)
    - String literals (single, double, template with ${})
    - Comments (line and block)
    @End Reasoning

    Note: In production, this would execute the lexer test suite
    Note: Real implementation would: exec test_javascript_lexer.runa
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the JavaScript parser test suite. Mirrors
run_lexer_tests as the integration-point stub for the
test_javascript_parser.runa harness.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 (suite passed). The inline @Reasoning describes the
parser surface (declarations, functions, classes, statements,
expressions, literals, imports, template literals) the eventual
runner must cover.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Current behavior: always returns 0
- Future: invokes test_javascript_parser.runa and forwards its exit code
@End TestCases

Process called "run_parser_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Parser tests verify complete AST generation:
    - Variable declarations (var, let, const)
    - Functions (regular, arrow, async, generator)
    - Classes with methods and inheritance
    - All statement types (if, for, while, switch, try/catch, etc.)
    - All expression types (binary, unary, call, member, etc.)
    - Object and array literals with spread
    - Import/export statements
    - Template literals
    @End Reasoning

    Note: In production, this would execute the parser test suite
    Note: Real implementation would: exec test_javascript_parser.runa
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the JavaScript AST -> HIR translation suite.
Integration stub for the test_javascript_to_hir.runa harness that
covers node-type fidelity, metadata preservation, nested structures,
and JS-specific semantics (hoisting, this binding, prototypes).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 (suite passed). The inline @Reasoning enumerates the
translation invariants the eventual runner must verify.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Current behavior: always returns 0
- Future: invokes test_javascript_to_hir.runa and forwards its exit code
@End TestCases

Process called "run_hir_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    HIR translation tests verify JavaScript AST → HIR conversion:
    - All node types correctly translated
    - Metadata preserved (async flags, static flags, etc.)
    - Nested structures properly represented
    - Special JavaScript features (hoisting, this binding, prototypes)
    @End Reasoning

    Note: In production, this would execute the HIR translation test suite
    Note: Real implementation would: exec test_javascript_to_hir.runa
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the HIR -> JavaScript code-generation suite. Integration
stub for the test_hir_to_javascript.runa harness covering idiomatic
ES6+ output, indentation, semicolons, modern syntax, and operator
precedence.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 (suite passed). The inline @Reasoning enumerates the
emitter style invariants the eventual runner must verify.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Current behavior: always returns 0
- Future: invokes test_hir_to_javascript.runa and forwards its exit code
@End TestCases

Process called "run_codegen_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Code generation tests verify HIR → JavaScript code generation:
    - Idiomatic ES6+ JavaScript output
    - Proper indentation (2 spaces)
    - Semicolon placement
    - Modern syntax (arrow functions, classes, async/await)
    - Correct operator precedence
    @End Reasoning

    Note: In production, this would execute the code generation test suite
    Note: Real implementation would: exec test_hir_to_javascript.runa
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the JavaScript round-trip translation suite.
Integration stub for the test_javascript_round_trip.runa harness
that verifies semantic equivalence after JS -> HIR -> JS across
50+ programs covering all ES6+ features.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 (suite passed). The inline @Reasoning lists the round-trip
invariants the eventual runner must verify.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Current behavior: always returns 0
- Future: invokes test_javascript_round_trip.runa and forwards its exit code
@End TestCases

Process called "run_roundtrip_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Round-trip tests verify JavaScript → HIR → JavaScript preservation:
    - Semantic equivalence maintained
    - Syntax may differ but meaning preserved
    - All JavaScript features supported
    - Test programs: async functions, classes, destructuring, spread, etc.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: In production, this would execute the round-trip test suite
    Note: Real implementation would: exec test_javascript_round_trip.runa
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Updates SuiteResults counters after each sub-suite runs and prints
a per-suite pass/fail line. Centralized so all five run_*_tests
calls feed through one bookkeeping path instead of five copies of
counter-mutation code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Read total_suites at offset 0; write total_suites + 1.
2. If suite_result == 0 (pass): read passed_suites at offset 8,
   write +1, print "[SUITE PASSED] <name>".
3. Otherwise (any non-zero is fail): read failed_suites at offset 16,
   write +1, print "[SUITE FAILED] <name>".
4. Return 1 (unused but kept for signature consistency).
@End Implementation

Process called "update_results" takes results as Integer, suite_result as Integer, suite_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total be proc memory_get_integer with results, 0
    proc memory_set_integer with results, 0, total plus 1

    If suite_result is equal to 0:
        Let passed be proc memory_get_integer with results, 8
        proc memory_set_integer with results, 8, passed plus 1
        proc print_suite_success from suite_name
    Otherwise:
        Let failed be proc memory_get_integer with results, 16
        proc memory_set_integer with results, 16, failed plus 1
        proc print_suite_failure from suite_name
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verbose suite-of-suites banner. Beyond the title and separator it
also prints the list of five sub-suites this driver dispatches to,
giving CI consumers visibility into the expected work without
needing to read main's body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate and print: title "JAVASCRIPT COMPREHENSIVE TEST SUITE",
"=" separator (36 chars), an "info" intro, then five "- <suite>"
labels naming each sub-suite. Each string is deallocated after print.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_main_header" returns Integer:
    Let header be proc create_string from StringCore with "JAVASCRIPT COMPREHENSIVE TEST SUITE"
    proc print from header
    proc deallocate from Layout with header

    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with "===================================="
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Let info1 be proc create_string from StringCore with "Testing all JavaScript ES6+ features:"
    proc print from info1
    proc deallocate from Layout with info1

    Let info2 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Lexer (comprehensive tokenization)"
    proc print from info2
    proc deallocate from Layout with info2

    Let info3 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Parser (complete AST generation)"
    proc print from info3
    proc deallocate from Layout with info3

    Let info4 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- HIR Translation (AST → HIR)"
    proc print from info4
    proc deallocate from Layout with info4

    Let info5 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Code Generation (HIR → JavaScript)"
    proc print from info5
    proc deallocate from Layout with info5

    Let info6 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Round-Trip (50+ test programs)"
    proc print from info6
    proc deallocate from Layout with info6

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Visual separator emitted between sub-suite runs so CI log readers
can tell at a glance where one phase ends and the next begins.
Width matches the main banner so the visual structure is consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print an empty line via an empty string, then print a 36-character
"-" rule. Both strings are allocated, printed, and deallocated.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_suite_separator" returns Integer:
    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with ""
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Let line be proc create_string from StringCore with "------------------------------------"
    proc print from line
    proc deallocate from Layout with line

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[SUITE PASSED] <name>" line. Distinct format from per-test [PASS]
so a CI grep can separate suite-level from test-level wins.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[SUITE PASSED] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned
suite_name, deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_suite_success" takes suite_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[SUITE PASSED] "
    proc print from msg
    proc print from suite_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[SUITE FAILED] <name>" line. Distinct format from per-test [FAIL]
so CI consumers can immediately see which entire JavaScript phase
regressed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[SUITE FAILED] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned
suite_name, deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_suite_failure" takes suite_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[SUITE FAILED] "
    proc print from msg
    proc print from suite_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Suite-of-suites final summary. Includes a celebratory ALL TESTS
PASSED message on success and a SOME TESTS FAILED message on
failure so the CI log has a single human-readable verdict line at
the end regardless of how many sub-suites ran.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print "=" header, "FINAL RESULTS:" heading, three counter lines
(Total/Passed/Failed Suites). If failed_suites == 0 print "ALL
TESTS PASSED!"; otherwise print "SOME TESTS FAILED!". Counter
values use type-checked field access (results.total_suites etc.).
@End Implementation

Process called "print_final_results" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let header be proc create_string from StringCore with "===================================="
    proc print from header
    proc deallocate from Layout with header

    Let summary be proc create_string from StringCore with "FINAL RESULTS:"
    proc print from summary
    proc deallocate from Layout with summary

    Let total_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Total Suites: "
    proc print from total_msg
    proc print_int with results.total_suites
    proc deallocate from Layout with total_msg

    Let passed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Passed Suites: "
    proc print from passed_msg
    proc print_int with results.passed_suites
    proc deallocate from Layout with passed_msg

    Let failed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Failed Suites: "
    proc print from failed_msg
    proc print_int with results.failed_suites
    proc deallocate from Layout with failed_msg

    If results.failed_suites is equal to 0:
        Let success be proc create_string from StringCore with "ALL TESTS PASSED!"
        proc print from success
        proc deallocate from Layout with success

    Otherwise:
        Let failure be proc create_string from StringCore with "SOME TESTS FAILED!"
        proc print from failure
        proc deallocate from Layout with failure
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Local integer formatter so this suite has no dependency on stdlib
formatting allocators. Zero and negative inputs are handled explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. value == 0 -> print "0", return.
2. Allocate 32-byte buffer; walk position from 31 downward writing
   48 + (temp % 10), dividing temp by 10 each pass.
3. For negatives, operate on -temp and write '-' (45) at the final
   position.
4. Increment position, print buffer+position as a C string, deallocate.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_int" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Let zero be proc create_string from StringCore with "0"
        proc print from zero
        proc deallocate from Layout with zero
        Return 1
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let position be 31
    Let temp be value

    If temp is less than 0:
        Set temp to -temp
    End If

    While temp is greater than 0:
        Let digit be temp modulo by 10
        Let char be 48 plus digit
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, char
        Set position to position minus 1
        Set temp to temp divided by 10
    End While

    If value is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, 45
        Set position to position minus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    Let str_ptr be buffer plus position
    proc print from str_ptr

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of JavaScript Comprehensive Test Suite Runner
